The paper deals with a random process involving queues and priority scheduling, which are fundamental topics in computer science. The focus on priority queues and the analysis of their performance suggests that the paper belongs to the category of data structures (cs.DS). The technical connection between balls-into-bins processes and priority scheduling suggests that the paper may also belong to the category of information theory (cs.IT). The analysis of the expected rank and worst-case cost of the process suggests that the paper may belong to the category of probability (cs.PR) or discrete mathematics (cs.DM). Finally, the mention of a new concurrent priority queue implementation suggests that the paper may also belong to the category of control systems (cs.SY).
